n- Conclusion: switch_2 is misconfigured at both control plane (runtime JSON failed to load, thrift access failing) and data plane (incorrect P4 header layout).\n\nFault localization\n- The fault is localized to switch_2:\n  - Packets are forwarded from switch_1 toward switch_2 but do not reach host_2.\n  - switch_2 is not inspectable via Thrift and shows a runtime JSON load error.\n  - switch_2’s P4 program deviates from switch_1 with an invalid IPv4 header definition, likely causing table matches to fail and default drop behavior.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Primary root cause: switch_2 is running an inconsistent and incorrect P4 program (malformed IPv4 header struct with bit<6> identification). This likely causes misparsing of IPv4 fields and failed matches in ipv4_lpm, resulting in drops.\n- Contributing factors:\n  - Runtime table programming on switch_2 likely did not apply due to “JSON input file cannot be opened.”\n  - Thrift connectivity to switch_2 fails, preventing verification or correction of table entries.\n\nAssessment of network health\n- Network health is poor: end-to-end connectivity is broken due to switch_2’s data-plane and control-plane misconfiguration.\n- switch_1 and both hosts are healthy and behaving as expected.\n- switch_2 is the abnormal component.\n\nRelevant evidence\n- Ping failures from both hosts (timeouts).\n- Host interfaces up with correct IPs and ARP entries; zero RX on both hosts.\n- switch_1 bmv2 logs: table hits and forwarding to port 2; packet transmitted.\n- switch_2 bmv2 logs: runtime JSON load error; no packet processing logs.\n- bmv2_show_tables success on switch_1; failure to connect on switch_2.\n- P4 program diff: switch_2 IPv4 header identification defined as 6 bits vs 16 bits on switch_1.\n\nConfidence\n- High, based on corroborating logs, tool outputs, and P4 program differences.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 9482, "outpu